<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn212">  212  Unfortunately, before we can get on with the story, we are faced with a complication: though a radio programme is being broadcast, it is also an account of actual events unfolding in the public house. There is also some confusion as to who is saying what. Joyce, partly to allow us more certainly to differentiate between the speakers, uses three main variants of the words <i>said he</i>: &lsquo;sagd he,&rsquo; &lsquo;sayd he,&rsquo; and &lsquo;sazd he.&rsquo; These are used as tags indicating the sailor, the agent, and the tailor, respectively. A strange fourth form &mdash; &lsquo;szed he&rsquo; &mdash; appears twice and seems to double for &lsquo;sazd he.&rsquo;  </div>
